To style your HTML form to resemble a Gradio card, you would need to use CSS to apply styling rules that will give your elements the desired appearance. Gradio typically has a modern, card-style interface which often includes a clean look with some padding, shadows, rounded corners, and interactive elements like buttons with hover effects.

Here's a simple example of how you can use CSS to mimic a card-style design for your form:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>

<head>
    <style>
        .container {
            width: 80%;
            margin: 50px auto;
            padding: 20px;
            border-radius: 8px;
            box-shadow: 0 4px 8px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.2);
            transition: 0.3s;
            background: white;
        }

        .container:hover {
            box-shadow: 0 8px 16px 0 rgba(0,0,0,0.2);
        }

        h2 {
            text-align: center;
            color: #333;
        }

        .upload-form {
            display: flex;
            flex-direction: column;
            align-items: center;
        }

        .upload-btn {
            background-color: #007bff;
            color: white;
            padding: 10px 20px;
            margin: 10px 0;
            border: none;
            border-radius: 5px;
            cursor: pointer;
            transition: background-color 0.3s ease;
        }

        .upload-btn:hover {
            background-color: #0056b3;
        }

        input[type="file"] {
            margin: 10px 0;
        }
    </style>
</head>

<body>
    <div class="container">
        <h2>Upload Video</h2>
        <form action="/upload/video" method="post" enctype="multipart/form-data" class="upload-form">
            <input type="file" name="video" accept="video/*" required>
            <br><br>
            <button type="submit" class="upload-btn">Upload</button>
        </form>
    </div>
</body>

</html>
```

This code styles the `.container` div to look like a card, with padding, a shadow, and a hover effect that emphasizes the shadow. The `<h2>` header is centered and colored, while the form elements are styled to be visually clear and pleasant, with the submit button colored and reacting on hover.

This is a simple example, and you may need to adjust the CSS to fit the exact look and interactivity you want for your application, especially if you want to closely match the specific aesthetics of Gradio cards. If you already know the exact styling rules used by Gradio, you can replicate them directly in your own CSS.

Consider adding a reference to a CSS framework like Bootstrap if you would like to easily use pre-styled components that could also resemble a Gradio card style with minimal effort:

```html
<head>
    <!-- Add Bootstrap CDN for easy styling -->
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="https://stackpath.bootstrapcdn.com/bootstrap/4.5.2/css/bootstrap.min.css">
</head>
```

Then, you can use Bootstrap classes to get the desired look with significantly less custom CSS required.

The HTML provided creates a user interface for uploading video files, complete with a preview of the video selected by the user. The code consists of an HTML form with a file input element, label for user-friendly interactions, a video element for previews, some utility divs to display messages and a loading indicator, and some styles to make the page look presentable.

Here's how the code works:

1. A user selects a video file by clicking the "Choose File" button (styled label), which activates the hidden file input field (`<input type="file" ...>`).

2. The `change` event listener on the file input field is triggered when a user selects a file. The event listener performs several tasks:
   - It reads the file chosen by the user and attaches the file name to a span with class `.file-input-label`.
   - It displays a loader (styled div with class `.loader`) to simulate an upload process.
   - It uses a `FileReader` object to read the contents of the selected file as a data URL which is then assigned to the `src` attribute of the video element. This allows a preview of the video to be displayed before it is uploaded.

3. There's a simulation of a 3-second upload process (using `setTimeout`). Once that simulation concludes, it hides the loader and displays an "Upload complete!" message via a span with class `.upload-msg`.

However, the code has a few issues and potential areas for improvement:

- A hardcoded 3-second timeout simulates the completion of the upload. In a real-world scenario, this should be removed, and the actual upload status needs to be handled by the backend and notified to the frontend perhaps via JavaScript fetch/AJAX calls.

- The "Upload complete" message is misleading because the file isn't actually being uploaded to the server during the timeout. The user might think the file has been uploaded when it hasn't been.

- The `action` attribute of the form element points to `/upload/video`, which is the endpoint in your server where the video file should be received and processed.

Here is an updated script section that removes the simulation and instead relies on the actual form submission to determine when the file upload is complete:

```html
<script>
    document.getElementById('video').addEventListener('change', function (e) {
        var file = e.target.files[0];
        var videoPreview = document.getElementById('video-preview');
        var fileName = file.name;
        document.querySelector('.file-input-label').innerText = fileName;
        document.querySelector('.upload-msg').innerText = '';
        document.querySelector('.loader').style.display = 'none'; // Initially, loader is not shown

        // Display video preview
        var reader = new FileReader();
        reader.onload = function (event) {
            videoPreview.src = event.target.result;
        };
        reader.readAsDataURL(file);
    });

    document.querySelector('.upload-form').addEventListener('submit', function (e) {
        // Show the loader when the form is submitted
        document.querySelector('.loader').style.display = 'inline-block';
        document.querySelector('.upload-msg').innerText = 'Uploading...';
        document.querySelector('.container').classList.add('uploading');
    });
</script>
```

This script updates the 'Uploading...' message to appear when the form is submitted. It assumes there is a loader element that could be a spinner or progress bar (not included in the snippet provided). Proper backend handling and client-side scripting with AJAX or Fetch API can present the user with a dynamic response to the actual upload process.

